A082031.name: Expansion of exp(2x)/(1-x)^3.
formula: Based on this series the ZeilbergerRecurrence command in Maple 17 produces the first-order recurrence (n^2 - 3*n + 4)*a(n) = 2^(n+2) + n*(n^2 - n + 2)*a(n-1). Using this it is easy to verify the second-order recurrence conjectured above by Mathar.

The sequence b(n) := n!*(1 + n*(n-1)/2) = n!*A000124(n-1) also satisfies Mathar's recurrence equation but with starting values b(0) = b(1) = 1. This yields the finite continued fraction expansion a(n)/b(n) = 1/(1 - 4/(5 - 2/(6 - 4/(7 - ... - (2*n - 2)/(n + 4) )))), valid for n >= 2.

It can be shown that a(n+1)/b(n+1) = 1 + 16*( sum {k = 0..n} 2^k/((k + 1)!*(k^4 + 3*k^2 + 4)) ). Taking the limit gives the series acceleration result e^2 = 1 + 16*( sum {k = 0..inf} 2^k/((k+1)!*(k^4 + 3*k^2 + 4)) ). Cf. A082030 and A052124. (End)

Further remarks from Jonathan R. Love (japanada11(AT)yahoo.ca), Mar 08 2007: (Start) For 2<n<10: a(9) = 16 because it can be written as 9, 4(1)4, 3(3)3, 2(5)2, or 1(7)1. All (n) can be expanded into a(n) different terms; for example, 2(5)2 can be written as 2(11111)2, 2(131)2, 2(212)2, or 2(5)2: 4 terms, since a(5) = 4. So a(9) = 1 + a(1) + a(3) + a(5) + a(7). Since a(7) = 1 + a(1) + a(3) + a(5), a(9) = a(7) + a(7) = 2 * a(7).

For n=10 or 11: Using the rules for 2<n<10, a(10) would be 32, but since one of these terms is the number itself, in this case 10 and only single-digit numbers can be used, one term must be subtracted. a(10) = 2 * a(8) - 1 = 31.

For 12<n<20: The same rules for 2<n<10 apply, because for 12 and up, the term taken away from 10 and 11 is added into the terms: a(12) = 62 = 2 * a(10). a(10) = 2 * a(8) - 1, so a(12) = 4 * a(8) - 2: 1 for (12) and one for 1(10)1.
For 20: Including the terms subtracted in 12<n<20, another term must be subtracted for (10)(10).

For 21<=n: From this point on, all possible terms are 9(a(n-18))9 + 8(a(n-16))8 + 7(a(n-14))7 + 6(a(n-12))6 + 5(a(n-10))5 + 4(a(n-8))4 + 3(a(n-6))3 + 2(a(n-4))2 + 1(a(n-2))1. If a(n-20) were to be included, it would need to be (10)(a(n-20))(10) and 10s can't be included. So everything must subtract a(n-20) from the total of 2 * a(n-2). For example, a(24) = 3956 = 2 * a(22) - a(4). (End)

Let c(n,k) (1<=k<=n) = number of compositions of n into parts of size <= k (cf. A126198). Then a(n) = Sum_{i=0..floor(n/2)} c(n,9). This follows by consideration of the central term, which may be any of n, n-2, n-4, ..., n-2i, ...; the prefix is then a composition of i into parts of size <= 9. - _N. J. A. Sloane_ Mar 09 2007

A082374.name: Set of n such that the prime quadruple p(n), p(n+1), p(n+2), p(n+3) does not have a solution for the congruence p(n+1)^x - p(n)^x == p(n+2) mod p(n+3).

A082375.name: Irregular triangle read by rows: row n begins with n and decreases by 2 until 0 or 1 is reached, for n >= 0.
formula: T(n, m) = n - 2*m, m = 0, 1, ..., floor(n/2), n >= 0 (see the name and programs). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Feb 17 2020

A082376.name: First of quadruple of consecutive primes p1,p2,p3,p4 such that the congruence p2^x - p1^x == p3 (mod p4) has no solution.

A082377.name: Numbers n such that rad(n)-phi(n)<=1, where rad(n)=A007947(n) and phi(n)=A000010(n).

A082378.name: Positive integers that can be written in exactly one way as the product ab of positive integers where a+b is composite.

A082380.name: Number of 7/3+-power-free words over the alphabet {0,1}.
formula: Let L = lim a(n)^(1/n); then L exists since a(n) is submultiplicative. 1.2206318 < L < 1.22064482 (Shur 2012); the gap between the bounds can be made less than any given constant. Empirically, the upper bound is precise: L=1.2206448... . - _Arseny Shur_, Apr 26 2015

A082381.name: Sequence of the squared digital root of a number until 1 or 4 is reached. The initial numbers 1,2,..n are not output.

A082382.name: Table which contains in row n the track of n->A003132(n) until reaching 1 or 4.

A082385.name: For each n append T(n), T(T(n)), T^3(n), ..., T^r(n), where T(n) = A055012(n) and r is the smallest integer such that T^r(n) is one of the following numbers: 1, 55, 136, 153, 160, 370, 371, 407, 919.

A082386.name: Let S(0) = {1} and for k >= 1, let S(k) = {S(k-1), S(k-1), 2T}, where T = sum of terms in S(k-1). Sequence is S(infinity).

A082387.name: Numbers k such that (5^k + 2^k)/7 is prime.

A082388.name: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2; further terms are defined by rules that for k >= 2, a(2^k-i) = a(2^k+i) for 1 <= i <= 2^k-1 and a(2^k) = a(2^(k-1)) + Sum_{i < 2^k} a(i).
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e) = A006012(e), a(p^e) = 1 for odd prime p. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Jul 31 2018

A082390.name: Numbers on a computer numpad, read in a clockwise spiral.

A082391.name: Start with the sequence a(1 to 4) = "1,3,2,3". Then in step s, append "1", "1,2", or "1,2,3", whichever ends with a(s+2).

A082392.name: Expansion of (1/x) * sum(k>=0, x^2^k/(1-2x^2^(k+1))).
formula: a((2*n+1)*2^p-1) = 2^n, p >= 0 and n >= 0. - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Feb 11 2013

A082393.name: Let p = n-th prime of the form 4k+1, take the integer solution (x,y) to the Pellian equation x^2 - p*y^2 = 1 with the smallest y >= 1; sequence gives value of y.

A082394.name: Let p = n-th prime of the form 4k+3, take the solution (x,y) to the Pellian equation x^2 - p*y^2 = 1 with x and smallest y >= 1; sequence gives value of y.

A082395.name: Number of shifted Young tableaux with height <= 3.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n}(-1)^(k+1)*binomial(n, k)*binomial(k-1, floor(k/2)). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 18 2003

A082396.name: Numbers n such that n/(2*n-A082851(n)) is an integer.

A082397.name: Number of directed aggregates of height <= 2 with n cells.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n}(-1)^(k+1)*binomial(n+1, k+1)*binomial(k, floor((k-1)/2)). E.g.f.: -exp(x)*int(-BesselI(1, 2*x)+BesselI(2, 2*x), x)-exp(x)*(-BesselI(1, 2*x)+BesselI(2, 2*x)). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 18 2003

A082398.name: Number of directed, diagonally convex polyominoes with n cells.

A082399.name: a(1) = 1; thereafter, a(n) is the smallest nonnegative number such that the number Sum_{i=1..n} a(i)*10^(n-i) is divisible by n.

A082400.name: Numbers k such that 2^k + 3^(k-1) is prime.

A082401.name: a(n)=A005374(n)-floor(r*n) where r is the positive root of x^3+x-1=0.
formula: It seems that sum(k=1, n, a(k)) is asymptotic to C*n where C=0.53...>1/2

A082402.name: Number of n-node labeled weakly connected acyclic digraphs.
formula: E.g.f.: log(B(x)) where B(x) is e.g.f. for A003024.

A082403.name: E.g.f.: 1-1/B(x) where B(x) is e.g.f. for A003024.

A082404.name: Triangle in which n-th row gives trajectory of n under the map x -> x/2 if x is even, x -> x-1 if x is odd, stopping when we reach 1.

A082406.name: Numbers k such that k divides Sum_{j=1..k} binomial(2j,j).
formula: Is a(n) asymptotic to c*n*log(n) with 2 < c < 2.3?

A082407.name: define u(k) as u(1)=1 u(k)=binomial(2*u(k-1),u(k-1)) (mod k), sequence gives values of k such that u(k)=0.
formula: It seems that a(n) is asymptotic to c*n with 6.1 < c < 6.2.

A082408.name: Least k such that the continued fraction for n/k contains no element >2.

A082409.name: Composite numbers n such that the continued fraction for n/k contains no 2 for any 1<=k<=n.

A082410.name: a(1)=0. Thereafter, the sequence is constructed using the rule: for any k >= 0, if a(1), a(2), ..., a(2^k+1) are known, the next 2^k terms are given as follows: a(2^k+1+i) = 1 - a(2^k+1-i) for 1 <= i <= 2^k.

A082411.name: Second-order linear recurrence sequence with a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2).

A082415.name: Numbers n such that in all partitions of n into distinct coprimes these coprimes are also mutually relatively prime.

A082417.name: Numbers n such that P(n) < P(n+1) > P(n+2), where P(n) = largest prime factor of n (A006530).

A082418.name: Numbers n such that P(n) > P(n+1) < P(n+2), where P(n) = largest prime factor of n (A006530).

A082419.name: Numbers n such that P(n+2) < P(n) < P(n+1), where P(n) = largest prime factor of n (A006530).

A082420.name: Numbers n such that P(n) < P(n+2) < P(n+1), where P(n) = largest prime factor of n (A006530).

A082421.name: Numbers n such that P(n+1) < P(n) < P(n+2), where P(n) = largest prime factor of n (A006530).

A082422.name: Numbers n such that P(n) > P(n+2) > P(n+1), where P(n) = largest prime factor of n (A006530).

A082423.name: a(1)=1, a(n)=ceiling(n/(n+1)*sum(k=1,n-1,a(k))).
formula: Apparently a(n) is asymptotic to C*2^n/sqrt(n) where C=0.6... [corrected by _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 16 2019]

A082424.name: Coefficient of s(2n) in s(n,n) * s(n,n) * s(n,n) * s(n,n) * s(n,n) * s(n,n), where s(n,n) is the Schur function indexed by two parts of size n, s(2n) is the Schur function corresponding to the trivial representation and * represents the inner or Kronecker product.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{gamma} Chi^{(n, n)}( gamma )^6/z(gamma) the sum is over all partitions gamma of 2n Chi^lambda(gamma) is the value of the symmetric group character z(gamma) is the size of the stablizer of the conjugacy class of symmetric group indexed by the partition gamma

A082425.name: a(1)=1, a(n) = n*(a(n-1) + a(n-2) + ... + a(2) + a(1)) - 1.
formula: In the following remarks we use an offset of 1, i.e., a(1) = 1, a(2) = 1, a(3) = 5, ... . For n >= 2, a(n) = n*n!*Sum_{k = 2..n} 1/(k*(k-1)*k!). For n >= 2, a(n) = 3*n*n! - Sum_{k = 0..n} (k + 1)!*binomial(n,k). Lim_{n -> infinity} a(n)/(n*n!) = 3 - e. E.g.f.: 3*(1+t)/(1-t)^3 - exp(t)*(3-t)/(1-t)^3. a(n) = A083746(n+2) - A001339(n).

Recurrence relation: a(2) = 1, a(3) = 5, a(n) = (n+2)*a(n-1) - (n-1)*a(n-2) for n >=4. Recurrence relation: a(2) = 1, a(n) = (n^2*a(n-1)+1)/(n-1) for n >= 2. The recurrence relation x(n) = (n^2*x(n-1)-1)/(n-1), for n >= 2, has the general solution x(n) = n*n!*x(1) - a(n); particular solutions are A007808 (x(1) = 1) and A001339 (x(1) = 3). (End)

A082429.name: a(n) is the cardinality of the smallest subset S1 of S={1,2,3,...,n} such that every element of S is either in S1 or is the sum of two elements of S1.

A082431.name: a(n) = the smallest prime p such that there are exactly n sets of consecutive primes, each of which has an arithmetic mean of p.

A082432.name: a(n) = p - A072181(n), where p is the least prime > A072181(n) + 1.

A082433.name: a(n) = A072181(n) - p, where p is the largest prime < A072181(n) - 1.

A082434.name: Let q_n be least prime > x_n := 1 + 2*n!; sequence gives a(n) = q_n-x_n+1.

A082437.name: Coefficient of s(2n) in s(n,n) * s(n,n) * s(n,n) * s(n,n) * s(n,n), where s(2n) is the Schur function corresponding to the trivial representation, s(n,n) is a Schur function corresponding two the two row partition and * represents the inner or Kronecker product of symmetric functions.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{gamma} Chi^{(n, n)}( gamma )^5/z(gamma) the sum is over all partitions gamma of 2n Chi^lambda(gamma) is the value of the symmetric group character z(gamma) is the size of the stablizer of the conjugacy class of symmetric group indexed by the partition gamma

A082446.name: a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(2)=0; thereafter, if k>=0 and a block of the first 3*2^k terms is known, then a(3*2^k+i)=1-a(i) for 0<=i<3*2^k.

A082447.name: a(n) = the number k such that s(k)=0 where s(0)=n and s(i)=s(i-1)-(s(i-1) modulo i).

A082448.name: Add 1, multiply by 1, add 2, multiply by 2, etc.; start with 4.

A082449.name: Let f(p) = greatest prime divisor of p-1. Sequence gives smallest prime which takes at least n steps to reach 2 when f is iterated.

A082450.name: a(n) = 5*(n^2-n+2)/2.
formula: a(n) = 5*n + a(n-1)-5 for n>0, a(0)=5. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 08 2010

A082451.name: Sum over divisors d of n of Kronecker symbol (-60, d).
formula: Expansion of q * f(-q^3) * f(-q^5) / (chi(-q) * chi(-q^15)) in powers of q where f(), chi() are Ramanujan theta functions.
Expansion of eta(q^2) * eta(q^3) * eta(q^5) * eta(q^30) / (eta(q) * eta(q^15)) in powers of q.
a(n) is multiplicative with a(2^e) = a(3^e) = a(5^e) = 1, a(p^e) = e+1 if p == 1, 2, 4, 8 (mod 15), a(p^e) = (1 + (-1)^e)/2 if p == 7, 11, 13, 14 (mod 15).

A082452.name: a(n)=2n+1 where n is such that A083344(n) is not zero.

A082453.name: a(n)=2n+1 where n is such that A083344(n) is zero.

A082456.name: a(n)=p[n]+p[n-1]-a(n-1), with a[0]=0,a[1]=127, p[i] = i-th prime.

A082458.name: Multiply by 1, add 1, multiply by 2, add 2, etc., starting with 0.
formula: For n>=2, a(2n)=floor(e*n!)-1, a(2*n+1)=(n+1)*(floor(e*n!)-1). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 28 2003

A082459.name: Multiply by 1, add 1, multiply by 2, add 2, etc.

A082460.name: a(n) = pi(n) - a(n - 1) = A000720(n) - a(n - 1).
formula: a(1) = 0; after which, a(2n) = 1 and a(2n+1) = A000720(2n+1)-1. - _Antti Karttunen_, Nov 17 2019

A082461.name: Non-palindromic numbers whose decimal expansion is a concatenation of the form a_1 a_2 a_3 ... a_{k-1} a_k a_k a_{k-1} ... a_2 a_1 (k >= 1) or a_1 a_2 a_3 ... a_{k-1} a_k a_{k-1} ... a_2 a_1 (k >= 2) for positive integers a_1, ..., a_k. For i>1, a_i may have leading zeros.

A082462.name: Let chi(k) = 1 if prime(k+1) - prime(k) = 2, = 0 otherwise; sequence gives a(n) = sum_{k <= n} chi(k).

A082463.name: Numbers n such that A072181(n) + 1 is prime.

A082465.name: Least k>=1 such that n^2+kn+1 is prime.

A082466.name: Least k>=1 such that n^2+kn-1 and n^2+kn+1 are twin primes.

A082467.name: Least k>0 such that n-k and n+k are both primes.

A082468.name: a(n) is the smallest positive integer such that k=n where k is the least positive integer such that n-k and n+k are both primes.

A082469.name: If n==1 or mod(n,2)==0 or mod(n,5)==0 then -1, otherwise a(n) is the smallest nonnegative integer k such that the concatenation 1(k)2(k)3(k)...(k)n is a prime.

A082470.name: a(n) is the number of k >= 0 such that k! + prime(n) is prime.

A082471.name: a(1)=1, a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n-1} Fibonacci(k)*a(k).
formula: G.f.: 1 + x/(G(0)-2*x) where G(k) = 1 + x + x*F(k+1) - x*(F(k+2)+1)/G(k+1); F(k) is the k-th Fibonacci number; (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 08 2012

A082472.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n-1} a(k)*2^k.
formula: a(n) is asymptotic to c*2^(n*(n-1)/2) where c = Product_{k>=1} (1+1/(2*2^k)) = 1.5894873526.....
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = x * (1 + A(2*x) / (1 - x)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 04 2020

A082473.name: Numbers n such that n = phi(x)*core(x) for some x <= n, where phi(x) is the Euler totient function and core(x) the squarefree part of x.
formula: The number of terms not exceeding x is ~ c * sqrt(x), where c = Product_{p prime} (1 + 1/sqrt(p*(p-1)) - 1/p) = 1.3651304521... (Janous, 1988). - _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 10 2021

A082474.name: Numbers n such that n=phi(x)*sigma(x) for some x<=n.

A082475.name: Prime index i for consecutive primes p(i),p(i+1),p(i+2),p(i+3) that do not have a solution for the congruences p(i)^x+p(i+1)^x = p(i+2) mod p(i+3) and p(i+1)^x-p(i)^x = p(i+2) mod p(i+3).

A082476.name: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} mu(d)^2*tau(d)^2.
formula: a(n) = abs(sum(d|n, mu(d)*tau_3(d^2))), where tau_3 is A007425. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Mar 29 2010
a(n) = tau_5(rad(n)) = A061200(A007947(n)). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jun 24 2010

A082477.name: Number of divisors d of n such that d+1 is also a divisor of n+1.

A082478.name: Number of divisors d of n such that (d+1) is a divisor of (n+1) and (d+2) a divisor of (n+2).

A082480.name: a(n) = Product_{k=1..n} (F(k)+1) where F(k) denotes the k-th Fibonacci number.

A082481.name: Number of 1's in binary representation of C(2n,n).

A082483.name: Numbers n such that 1/(5-s(n)) is an integer where s(k)=sum(i=1,k,1/2^floor(sqrt(i))).

A082484.name: First of four consecutive primes p, q, r, s such that neither of the congruences p^x+q^x = r (mod s) and q^x-p^x = r (mod s) has a solution.

A082485.name: Numbers n such that 1/(2-s(n)) is an integer where s(k)=sum(i=1,k,1/3^floor(sqrt(i))).

A082486.name: Decimal expansion of the constant c satisfying sum(k>=1,1/c^sqrtint(k))=1 where sqrtint(x)=floor(sqrt(x)).

A082488.name: a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..n} C(n,k) * C(n+k,k) * C(n+2*k,k) * C(n+3*k,k).
formula: exp( Sum_{n >= 1} a(n)*x^n/n ) = 1 + x + 13*x^2 + 893*x^3 + 99125*x^4 + 13706093*x^5 + ... appears to have integer coefficients. - _Peter Bala_, Jan 13 2016

A082489.name: a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..n} C(n,k) * C(n+k,k) * C(n+2*k,k) * C(n+3*k,k) * C(n+4*k,k).
formula: exp( Sum_{n >= 1} a(n)*x^n/n ) = 1 + x + 61*x^2 + 38101*x^3 + 42394381*x^4 + ... appears to have integer coefficients. - _Peter Bala_, Jan 13 2016

A082490.name: Exponent of highest power of 3 dividing sum(0<=k<n, C(2n,n)).

A082491.name: a(n) = n! * d(n), where n! = factorial numbers (A000142), d(n) = subfactorial numbers (A000166).
formula: a(n) = n! * d(n) where d(n) = A000166(n).
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n, k)^2 * (-1)^k * (n - k)!^2 * k!.

A082492.name: Integer n expressed in bases from n, n-1, ..., 1.

A082496.name: Numbers of the form 2p+1, where p and p+2 are a pair of twin primes.

A082499.name: Take a string of n x's and insert n-1 ^'s and n-1 pairs of parentheses in all possible legal ways. Sequence gives number of distinct values when x = sqrt(2).

A082500.name: a(n) = ceiling(n/2) if n is odd, or prime(n/2) otherwise.

A082501.name: Grundy numbers for start position in 1 X n closed Dots and Boxes.

A082503.name: Grundy numbers for start position of 1 X n triangular Dots and Boxes.

A082504.name: Largest k such that the sum of sums of decimal digits of the next k numbers > n does not exceed 10.

A082505.name: a(n) = sum of (n-1)-th row terms of triangle A134059.
formula: Starting (1, 6, 12, 24, 48, ...) = binomial transform of [1, 5, 1, 5, 1, 5, ...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 18 2007
a(n) = (-6*n + 16) * a(n-1) + 2 * Sum_{k=1..n-1} a(k) * a(n-k) if n>1. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 23 2011

A082506.name: a(n) = gcd(2^n, n - phi(n)); largest power of 2 dividing cototient(n) = A051953(n).

A082507.name: Generated by a 3rd-order formal recursion with suitable initial values as follows: a(n) = n - a(n-1) - a(n-2) - a(n-3); a(0)=a(1)=a(2)=0.

A082508.name: Differences between consecutive primes that are powers of 2 in order of their appearance. Differences not powers of 2 are deleted from A001223.

A082509.name: Differences between consecutive primes being not powers of 2 in order of their appearance. Differences which are powers of 2 are omitted from A001223.

A082510.name: Differences of consecutive primes being divisible by 6 in order of their appearance in A001223: terms not divisible by 6 are omitted from A001223.

A082512.name: a(n) = p is the smallest prime introducing a consecutive prime-difference pattern as follows: [2,2n,2], i.e., [p, p+2, p+2+2n, p+2+2n+2] are consecutive primes. Increasing middle prime gap in the immediate neighborhood of two small gaps(=2); a(n) = 0 if no such pattern exists.

A082516.name: Differences between consecutive Niven (or Harshad) numbers.

A082517.name: Numbers n such that N(n+1) - N(n) sets a new record, where N(n) = A005349.

A082518.name: Palindromic primes whose digital root equals their middle digits.

A082519.name: Number of times that k^2 + (n-k)^2 is prime for 1 <= k <= n-1.

A082520.name: Palindromic Sophie Germain primes: both p and 2p+1 are palindromic primes.

A082522.name: Numbers of the form p^(2^k) with p prime and k>0.
formula: a(n) ~ n^2 log^2 n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Oct 19 2015
Sum_{n>=1} 1/a(n) = Sum_{k>=1} P(2^k) = 0.53331724743088069672..., where P is the prime zeta function. - _Amiram Eldar_, Nov 26 2020

A082523.name: Number of times k^2 + (n-k)^2 is a square for 1 <= k <= n-1.

A082524.name: a(1)=1, a(2)=2, then use the rule when a(n) is the end of a run, n appears a(n) times.
formula: (n-1)/tau < a(n) < n where tau is the golden ratio; k>=3 a(F(k))=F(k-1) where F(k) is the k-th Fibonacci number.

A082525.name: Numerators of coefficients in (1+x)^(1+x) power series.

A082526.name: Denominators of coefficients in (1+x)^(1+x) power series.

A082527.name: Least k such that x(k)=0 where x(1)=n x(k)=k^2*floor(x(k-1)/k^2).
formula: a(n) seems to be asymptotic to (c*n)^(1/3) where c=4.96....

A082528.name: Least k such that x(k)=0 where x(1)=n x(k)=k^3*floor(x(k-1)/k^3).
formula: a(n) seems to be asymptotic to (c*n)^(1/4) where c=6.76....

A082529.name: Numbers n such that n divides C(n(n+1),n+1)/n^2.

A082530.name: a(1)=1, a(n)=5*a(n-1)+1 if a(n-1) is odd, a(n)=a(n-1)/2+1 otherwise.
formula: For n>=2 sequence is 12-periodic with period (6, 4, 3, 16, 9, 46, 24, 13, 66, 34, 18, 10).

A082531.name: (-1)^n * coefficient of x^n in 1/x-1/(1-eta(x)) power series.

A082533.name: Number of primes p such that p can be expressed as the sum of consecutive primes with largest prime in the sum = n-th prime.

A082534.name: Greatest prime p such that p can be expressed as the sum of consecutive primes with largest prime in the sum = n-th prime.

A082536.name: a(1) = 1; for n > 1, a(n) = smallest number greater than a(n-1) such that a(n-1)*a(n)+1 is a cube.

A082538.name: Number of numbers k which give 1 after applying exactly n iterations of the 3k+1 algorithm (if a number is even, divide it by 2; if it is odd, multiply by 3 and add 1). This total includes numbers k which also give 1 for a smaller number of iterations (i.e., for this sequence we do not assume the algorithm halts when 1 is reached).

A082539.name: Primes p such that there is no prime q, q < p with q+1 dividing p+1.

A082540.name: Number of ordered quadruples (a,b,c,d) with gcd(a,b,c,d)=1 (1 <= {a,b,c,d} <= n).
formula: a(n) is asymptotic to c*n^4 with c=0.92393....
Lim_{n->infinity} n^4/a(n) =   zeta(4) = A013662 = Pi^4/90. - _Karl-Heinz Hofmann_, Apr 11 2021

A082542.name: a(n) = prime(n) + 2 - (prime(n) mod 4).
formula: a(n+1) = p + (-1/p) = p + (-1)^{(p-1)/2)}, where p is the n-th odd prime and (a/b) denotes the value of Legendre symbol. - _Lekraj Beedassy_, Mar 17 2005

A082543.name: Take a string of n x's and insert n-1 ^'s and n-1 pairs of parentheses in all possible ways. Sequence gives number of distinct integer values when x=sqrt(2).

A082544.name: Number of ordered quintuples (a,b,c,d,e) with gcd(a,b,c,d,e)=1 (1<= {a,b,c,d,e} <= n).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} mu(k)*floor(n/k)^5; a(n) is asymptotic to c*n^5 with c=0.9643....
Lim_{n->infinity} n^5/a(n) =   zeta(5) = A013663. - _Karl-Heinz Hofmann_, Apr 11 2021

A082545.name: a(n) = (2*n)! * Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k)/(n+k)!.
formula: a(n) = n! * [x^n] exp(x/(1 - x))/(1 - x)^(n+1). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 21 2017

A082546.name: Numbers n such that n=A082534(x)=A082534(y), where x<y.
formula: Let pi = i-th prime, pj = j-th prime, x<y, i<=x, j<=y, n = Largest prime of Sum_{i..x} pi, m= Largest prime of Sum_{j..y} pj. n such that n = m.

A082547.name: Number of primes p such that p can be expressed as the sum of distinct primes with largest prime in the sum = n-th prime.

A082548.name: a(n) is the number of values of k such that k can be expressed as the sum of distinct primes with largest prime in the sum equal to prime(n).
formula: a(n) = A007504(n-1) - 5 for n > 4. - _Seiichi Manyama_, Oct 02 2019

A082549.name: Numbers n such that concatenation of first n primes, separated by zeros, is prime.

A082550.name: Number of sets of distinct positive integers whose arithmetic mean is an integer, the largest integer of the set being n.
formula: a(n) = A008965(n) for odd n. - _Dimitri Papadopoulos_, Jan 18 2016
G.f.: -x/(1 - x) - Sum_{m >= 0} (phi(2*m + 1)/(2*m + 1)) * log(1 - 2*x^(2*m + 1)). - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Jul 13 2019

A082551.name: Denote sigma(n)-n by s(n); a(n)=1 if s(n)>n, a(n)=0 if s(n)=n, a(n)=-1 if s(n)<n.

A082552.name: Number of sets of distinct primes, the greatest of which is prime(n), whose arithmetic mean is an integer.

A082553.name: Number of sets of distinct positive integers whose geometric mean is an integer, the largest integer of a set is n.

A082554.name: Primes whose base-2 representation is a block of 1's, followed by a block of 0's, followed by a block of 1's.

A082555.name: Primes whose base 3 representation does not contain a 0.

A082560.name: a(1)=1, a(n)=2*a(n-1) if n is odd, or a(n)=a(n/2)+1 if n is even.
formula: if n is in A010737 : a(n)=n-1

A082561.name: a(1)=1, a(n)=3*a(n-1) if n is not a multiple of 3, or a(n)=a(n/3)+1 if n is a multiple of 3.

A082562.name: a(n) = number of values of m such that m can be expressed as the sum of distinct odd numbers with largest odd number in the sum = 2n+1.
formula: For n>2, a(n) = n^2-1. The values of m are all values from 2n+1 to (n+1)^2 except 2n+3 and n^2+2n-1. - _David Wasserman_, Sep 16 2004

A082563.name: a(1) = 3; for n>=1, a(n+1) is the smallest palindromic prime with a(n) as a central substring.

A082564.name: Expansion of eta(q)^2 * eta(q^2) / eta(q^4) in powers of q.
formula: Expansion of phi(-q) * phi(-q^2) in powers of q where phi() is a Ramanujan theta function. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 30 2007
Euler transform of period 4 sequence [ -2, -3, -2, -2, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 30 2007
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (32 t)) = 2^(11/2) (t/i) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is the g.f. for A033761. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 29 2014
G.f.: Product_{k>0} (1 - x^k)^2 / (1 + x^(2*k)). - _Michael Somos_, Mar 30 2007
a(n) = -2 * A129134(n) unless n=0. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 30 2007

A082566.name: Primes p such that p, 2p+1, 4p+3 are palindromic primes.

A082567.name: Palindromic time display in hours, minutes, seconds on a six spaced 24-hour digital clock, using hours 1-24.

A082568.name: First nontrivial square root of unity mod A033949(n), i.e., smallest x > 1 such that x^2 == 1 mod A033949(n).

A082569.name: a(1)=2; a(n)=ceiling(n*(a(n-1)-1/a(n-1))).
formula: a(n) = A090802(n, n-3) for n > 2. - _Ross La Haye_, Sep 26 2005

A082571.name: Continued fraction expansion of common logarithm of 7 = log_10 7.

A082572.name: a(n) is the least number m such that the arithmetic mean of the distinct primes dividing m equals n.

A082574.name: a(1)=1, a(n) = ceiling(r(3)*a(n-1)) where r(3) = (1/2)*(3 + sqrt(13)) is the positive root of X^2 = 3*X + 1.
formula: a(n) = floor(t(3)*r(3)^n) where t(3) = (1/6)*(1 + 5/sqrt(13)) is the positive root of 39*X^2 = 13*X + 1.
G.f.: 1/((1-x)*(1-3*x-x^2)). Partial sums of A006190. - _Paul Barry_, Jul 10 2004

A082575.name: Nonnegative numbers in (3*A005836) union (3*A005836 - 2) [A005836 lists the numbers with base-3 representation containing no 2].

A082576.name: Numbers n such that n^n has final digits the same as all digits of n.

A082577.name: a(n) = first digit to the right of decimal point of n*(sqrt(5)-1)/2.
formula: n*0.618033989..., discard integer, then extract first digit to right of decimal.

A082579.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: exp( x/(1-x)^2 ).
formula: Special values of the hypergeometric function 2F2: a(n)=n!*n*hypergeom([n+1, -n+1], [3/2, 2], -1/4), n >= 1. - _Karol A. Penson_, Jan 29 2004
E.g.f.: E(0)/2, where E(k) = 1 + 1/( 1 - x/(x + (1-x)^2*(k+1)/E(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 16 2013
a(n) = n!*y(n), with y(0) = 1, y(n) = (Sum_{k=0..n-1} (n-k)^2*y(k))/n. - _Benedict W. J. Irwin_, Jun 02 2016
E.g.f.: Product_{k>=1} 1/(1 - x^k)^(J_2(k)/k), where J_2() is the Jordan function (A007434). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 25 2019
a(n) = n*n!*Hypergeometric2F2([1-n, n+1], [3/2, 2], -1/4) with a(0) = 1. - _G. C. Greubel_, Feb 23 2021

A082580.name: A sum of Lah numbers and binomial coefficients.
formula: Formula: a(n) = Sum[ Lah[ n, k ] binomial[ 2 k, k ], { k, 0, n } ] where Lah[n, k] = binomial[ n - 1, k - 1 ] n! / k! are the Lah numbers. Recurrence: ( n + 3 ) a(n+3) - ( 3 n^2 + 17 n + 24 ) a(n+2) + 3 ( n + 3 )( n + 2 )( n + 1 ) a(n+1) - ( n + 2 )( n + 1 )^2 n a(n) = 0
a(n) ~ exp(4*sqrt(n) - n - 2) * n^(n - 1/2) / sqrt(2*Pi). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jun 07 2019

A082581.name: Binomial coefficients C(p, k), 2<=k<=p-2, sorted, with duplicates removed, p being prime.

A082582.name: Expansion of (1 + x^2 - sqrt( 1 - 4*x + 2*x^2 + x^4)) / (2*x) in powers of x.
formula: G.f. A(x) satisfies the equation 0 = 1 - (1 + x^2) * A(x) + x * A(x)^2. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 22 2003
G.f. A(x) satisfies A(x) = 1 / (1 + x^2 - x * A(x)). - _Michael Somos_, Mar 28 2011
G.f. A(x) = 1 / (1 + x^2 - x / (1 + x^2 - x / (1 + x^2 - ... ))) continued fraction. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 01 2011
Series reversion of x * A(x) is x * A007477(-x). - _Michael Somos_, Jul 22 2003
a(n+1) = a(n) + Sum(a(k)*a(n-k): k=2..n), a(0) = a(1) = 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Nov 13 2012
G.f.: 1 + x - x*G(0), where G(k)= 1 - 1/(1 - x/(1 - x/(1 - x/(1 - x/(x - 1/G(k+1) ))))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 12 2013
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-2} Sum_{j=0..n-k-1} C(n-k-2,j)*C(k,j)*C(k+j+2,j)/(j+1), n>1, a(0)=1, a(1)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Oct 18 2020
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-2} HypergeometricPFQ[{-k, 3 +k, k - n + 2}, {1, 2}, 1] for n >= 2. - _Peter Luschny_, Oct 18 2020

A082583.name: Quotients C(p, k)/p sorted, with duplicates removed, p being prime.

A082584.name: Fractal palindromic primes of first order.

A082585.name: a(1)=1, a(n) = ceiling(r(5)*a(n-1)) where r(5) = (1/2)*(5 + sqrt(29)) is the positive root of X^2 = 5*X + 1.
formula: For n > 3, a(n) = 6*a(n-1) - 4*a(n-2) - a(n-3); a(n) = floor(t(5)*r(5)^n) where t(5) = (1/10)*(1 + 7/sqrt(29)) is the positive root of 145*X^2 = 29*X + 1.
G.f.: 1/(1/Q(0) + 3*x^3 - 3*x) where Q(k) = 1 + k*(2*x+1) + 8*x - 2*x*(k+1)*(k+5)/Q(k+1) ; (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Mar 15 2013

A082586.name: Length of the run of consecutive equal digits in the decimal expansion of Pi beginning at position n and ignoring any immediately-previous equal digits.

A082587.name: G.f.: (3+x+x^2+2*x^3)/(1-x^2-x^4).
formula: a(n) = A000204(floor(n/2)) + 2 - n mod 2). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Aug 03 2013

A082588.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = Sum_{d | n and d < n} a(d)^2 for n > 1.
formula: a(p^(n+1)) = A007018(n) if p is a prime. - _Michael Somos_, May 19 2018

A082589.name: Fractal palindromic primes of third order.

A082590.name: Expansion of 1/((1 - 2*x)*sqrt(1 - 4*x)).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n+1} binomial(2*n+2, k) * sin((n - k + 1)*pi/2. - _Paul Barry_, Nov 02 2004
a(n) = Sum{k=0..n} C(2*n, n)*C(n, k)/C(2*n, 2*k) - _Paul Barry_, Mar 18 2007
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) + 2*(-3*n+1)*a(n-1) + 4*(2*n-1)*a(n-2) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 03 2012

A082591.name: Starting position of the first occurrence of n in the decimal expansion of Pi such that a(n) > a(n-1) for n >= 1.

A082593.name: Values in Pfennigs of German money before the introduction of the Euro.

A082594.name: Constant term when a polynomial of degree n-1 is fitted to the first n primes.

A082595.name: Let QR be the set of quadratic residues mod n: QR = {x^2 mod n, 1 <= x <= n-1}. Let MR be the set of values taken by 2^x mod n: MR = {2^x mod n, 0 <= x <= n-2}. Usually if QR is a subset of MR then n is prime and otherwise n is composite. Sequence gives numbers that violate this rule, i.e., composites where QR is a subset of MR and primes where QR is not a subset of MR.

A082596.name: a(n) is the number of values of k such that A077389(k) = A060863(n).

A082597.name: Number of sets of consecutive primes whose arithmetic mean is an integer, the largest prime of a set is n-th prime.

A082598.name: Palindromic prime units W appearing twice in first order fractal palindromic primes WmW.

A082599.name: Palindromic prime units W appearing four times in second order fractal palindromic primes WxWmWxW.

A082600.name: Palindromic prime units W appearing eight times in third-order fractal palindromic primes WvWxWvWmWvWxWvW, where parts WvWxWvW, WvW are also palindromic primes.

A082601.name: Tribonacci array: to get the next row, right-adjust the previous 3 rows and add them, then append a final 0.
formula: G.f.: x/(1 - x - x^2*y - x^3*y^2). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, May 30 2003
T(n,k) = Sum_{j=0..floor(k/2)} binomial(k-j,j)*binomial(n-k,k-j) for 0 <= k and k <= floor(2*n/3) with binomial(i,j) = 0 for i<j (see _Dennis P. Walsh_ at A078802).

Based on two integers p and q define the integer sequence U(n) by U(0) = 0 and U(1) = 0 and U(n+2) = Sum_{k=0..floor(2*n/3)} T(n,k)*p^k*q^(2*n-3*k) for n >= 0. That yields the g.f. f(p,q,x) = x^2/(1 - q^2*x - p*q*x^2 - p^2*x^3) and the recurrence U(n+3) = q^2*U(n+2) + p*q*U(n+1) + p^2*U(n) for n >= 0 with initial values U(0) = U(1) = 0 and U(2) = 1. For p = q = +/-1, you'll get tribonacci numbers A000073. For p = -1 and q = 1, you'll get A021913. (End)

A082602.name: Number of primes between successive Fibonacci numbers (including possibly the Fibonacci numbers themselves).

A082603.name: a(n) is the first prime greater than a(n-1) such that a(n)*a(n-1)+2 is a prime, with a(1)=3.

A082604.name: a(n) is the total number of positive integral solutions (x,y), order being taken into account, to the equation 1/x + 1/y + 1/z = 1/n.

A082605.name: Using Euler's 6-term sequence A014556, we define the partial recurrence relation a(0)=2, a(1)=3, a(2)=5; a(k) = 2*a(k-1) - 1 + (-1)^(k-1)*2^(k-2), 3 <= k <= 5.
formula: (a(k))_(k>=0) = 2^(k-2)*(4 + sum((-1)^r, r=2..k-1)) + 1, the empty sums corresponding to k=0, 1, 2 of course taken to be zero.

A082607.name: a(0)=1; for n > 0, a(n) = least k not included earlier such that k*a(n-1) - 1 is a square.

A082608.name: Squares pertaining to A082607. a(n) = A082607(n)*A082607(n+1)- 1.

A082609.name: Begin with 1 and then smallest number not included earlier such that a(n)*a(n+1) -1 is a cube.

A082610.name: Cubes pertaining to A082609. a(n) = A082609(n)*A082609(n+1)- 1.

A082611.name: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..k} T(i,k)/(i*(k-i+1)), (k>=1, 1<=n<=k), where T(,) is given in A080046.

A082612.name: Numbers n such that ((n-1)^2+1)/2 and n^2+1 and ((n+1)^2+1)/2 are prime if n is even or (n-1)^2+1 and (n^2+1)/2 and (n+1)^2+1 are prime if n is odd.

A082613.name: Smallest palindrome divisible by an n-th power.

A082614.name: a(n) = A082613(n) divided by the n-th power that divides it.

A082615.name: Palindromes such that the GCD of any pair of successive terms is a palindromic prime.

A082616.name: Palindromes such that the least common multiple of any pair of successive terms is a palindrome.

A082617.name: a(1) = 1, then squarefree palindromes such that a(n+1) = p*a(n) where p is a prime not dividing any previous term.

A082618.name: Primes pertaining to A082617. a(n) = A082617(n+1)/A082617(n).

A082620.name: a(1) = 1, then the smallest palindromic prime obtained by inserting digits anywhere in a(n-1).

A082621.name: a(1) = 2, then the smallest palindromic prime obtained by inserting digits anywhere in a(n-1) (including at the ends).

A082622.name: a(1) = 3, a(n) = smallest palindromic prime obtained by inserting two paired digits anywhere in a(n-1).

A082623.name: a(1) = 5, a(n) = smallest palindromic prime obtained by inserting two digits anywhere in a(n-1).

A082624.name: a(1) = 7, a(n) = smallest palindromic prime obtained by inserting digit anywhere in a(n-1).

A082625.name: Smallest palindromic prime that ends (on the least significant side) in prime(n).

A082626.name: Smallest palindromic prime that ends (the least significant side) in (2n-1) the n-th odd number, or 0 if no such number exists, e.g., for 2n-1 = 10k + 5, k>0.

A082630.name: Limit of the sequence obtained from S(0) = (1,1) and, for n > 0, S(n) = I(S(n-1)), where I consists of inserting, for i = 1, 2, 3..., the term a(i) + a(i+1) between any two terms for which 7*a(i+1) <= 11*a(i).
formula: The sequence appears to satisfy a(n) = 4*a(n-2) - a(n-4).
Conjecturally, a(n) = A143643(n-1) + A005246(n), for n => 2, as derived from comment above. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Sep 08 2013

A082632.name: Decimal expansion of lim_{y->infinity} y^2*(Re(zeta(1 + i/y)) - gamma).
formula: Equals lim_{y->infinity} y^2*(Re(zeta(1+i/y)) - gamma), where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620.

A082633.name: Decimal expansion of the 1st Stieltjes constant gamma_1 (negated).
formula: Using the abbreviations a = log(z^2 + 1/4)/2, b = arctan(2*z) and c = cosh(Pi*z) then gamma_1 = -(Pi/2)*Integral_{0..infinity} (a^2 - b^2)/c^2. The general case is for n >= 0 (which includes Euler's gamma as gamma_0) gamma_n = -(Pi/(n+1))* Integral_{0..infinity} sigma(n+1)/c^2, where sigma(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} (-1)^k*binomial(n,2*k)*b^(2*k)*a^(n-2*k). - _Peter Luschny_, Apr 19 2018

A082634.name: Numbers n which can be expressed as sum of d consecutive primes (where d>0 is a divisor of n).

A082635.name: Square array read by antidiagonals: degree of the K(2,p)^q variety.

A082636.name: a(n) = smallest number which can be expressed as sum of d consecutive primes in exactly n ways (where d>0 is a divisor of the number).

A082637.name: a(n) = smallest number which can be expressed as sum of d consecutive positive integers in exactly n ways (where d>0 is a divisor of the number).

A082639.name: Numbers n such that 2*n*(n+2) is a square.
formula: a(n) = 1/kappa(sqrt(2)/A001542(n)); a(n) = 1/kappa(sqrt(8)/A005319(n)) where kappa(x) is the sum of successive remainders by computing the Euclidean algorithm for (1, x). - _Thomas Baruchel_, Nov 29 2003

A082640.name: Triangle T(m,n) read by rows: unimodular triangulations of the grid P(m,n), m,n > 0, n <= m.

A082641.name: Triangle T(n,k) (n >= 1, 1 <= k <= n) read by rows, where T(n,k) = number of basic invariants of degree k for the cyclic group of order and degree n.

A082642.name: Expansion of Molien series for 5-dimensional representation of dihedral group of order 10.

A082646.name: Primes whose decimal expansions contain equal numbers of each of their digits.

A082647.name: Number of ways n can be expressed as the sum of d consecutive positive integers where d>0 is a divisor of n.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = A067742(n) + A131576(n). - _Omar E. Pol_, Feb 22 2017
Conjecture: a(n) = A001227(n) - A131576(n). - _Omar E. Pol_, Apr 18 2017

A082648.name: Consider f(m) = Sum_{k=1..m} k! (A007489) when m is very large; a(n) = n-th digit from end.

A082649.name: Triangle of coefficients in expansion of sinh^2(n*x) in powers of sinh(x).

A082650.name: Number of primes < n of form 1+k*spf(n), where spf(n) is the smallest prime factor of n (A020639).
formula: a(2*n)=A000720(2*n)-1; a(n)=0 iff n=1 or n prime, a(A008578(n))=1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Sep 11 2003

A082651.name: Positive integer values of n such that 5n^2+11 is a square.

A082652.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of squares that can be found in a k X n rectangular grid of little squares, for 1 <= k <= n.
formula: T(n, k) = Sum{ i = 0..min(n,k)} (n-i)*(k-i). - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Nov 17 2007

A082653.name: For smallest numbers k such that A082596(k) = n, sequence gives A060863(k).

A082654.name: Order of 4 mod n-th prime: least k such that prime(n) divides 4^k-1, n >= 2.
formula: a(1) = 0, and a(n) = order(4, prime(n)), also used exp_{prime(n)}(4), that is least exponent k >= 1 for which 4^k is congruent to 1 mod prime(n), for n >= 2. prime(n) = A000040(n). [rewritten by _Wolfdieter Lang_, Apr 10 2020]
a(n) = (1/2)*order(2, 3*prime(n)), for n >= 3. [Proof uses 4^k - 1 = (1+3)^k - 1 == 0 (mod 3), for k >= 0.] (End)

A082655.name: Number of distinct letters needed to spell English names of numbers 1 through n.

A082656.name: Trajectory of 39 under map x -> x/2 if x even, 3x+9 if x odd.

A082657.name: Integers expressible as the sum of a square and a triangular number in just one way.

A082658.name: Integers expressible as the sum of a square and a triangular number in exactly two distinct ways.

A082659.name: Integers expressible as the sum of a square and a triangular number in exactly three distinct ways.

A082660.name: Number of ways n can be expressed as the sum of a square and a triangular number.

A082661.name: Numbers n such that A082596(n) = A050221(n), sequence gives A060863(n).

A082662.name: Numbers k such that the odd part of k is less than sqrt(2k).

A082663.name: Odd semiprimes pq with p < q < 2p.

A082664.name: Numbers k such that A082647(k) = A000005(k) - 1.

A082666.name: a(1) = 0, for n > 1 if n = prime(k), then a(n) = k, otherwise a(n) = Sum_{d|n, d<n} a(d).

A082667.name: a(n) = floor(2n/3) * ceiling(2n/3) / 2.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + 2a(n-3) - 2a(n-4) - a(n-6) + a(n-7), (with 0,0,0 prefixed as in the Comments section). - _Clark Kimberling_, Apr 15 2012
a(n) = floor((n + 1)/3)*(n - floor((n + 1)/3)). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 06 2014

A082668.name: (10^n)-th zero of the Riemann Zeta function rounded to the nearest integer.

A082669.name: Let p(n) = upper member of n-th pair of twin primes; sequence gives a(n) = p(n)*(p(n)-1)/2.

A082670.name: Let p(n) = upper member of n-th pair of twin primes; sequence gives a(n) = p(n)!/2.

A082671.name: Numbers n such that (n!-2)/2 is a prime.

A082672.name: Numbers n such that (n! + 2)/2 is a prime.

A082673.name: a(n) is the least k >= n such that k!/n + 1 is prime.

A082674.name: Constant term when a polynomial of degree n is fitted to the first n+1 lower members of the twin prime pairs.

A082675.name: Constant term when a polynomial of degree n is fitted to the first n+1 upper members of the twin prime pairs.

A082676.name: Constant term of polynomial of degree n passing through the first n+1 consecutive prime-indexed primes.
formula: Prime-indexed primes (PIPS) are generated by prime(prime(x)) x=1, 2, ...

A082677.name: Arises from a social choice theory problem. Sequence is a transformation of the number of non-transitive quasitransitive distinct profiles with 3 alternatives and strict individual preferences.

A082678.name: Arises from a social choice theory problem. Sequence is a transformation of the number of non-transitive non-quasitransitive acyclical distinct profiles with 3 alternatives and strict individual preferences.

A082679.name: Number of Lego towers, one piece per floor, where every floor is perpendicular to the one below it (so we have a kind of 3-dimensional zigzag pattern).

A082680.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of 2-stack sortable n-permutations with k runs.

A082682.name: Algebraic degree of R(e^(-n * Pi)), where R(q) is the Rogers-Ramanujan continued fraction.

A082683.name: Smaller of the two prime numbers whose product is A082663(n).

A082684.name: Larger of the two prime numbers whose product is A082663(n).

A082731.name: a(n) is the smallest number k such that A033880(k)= n, or 0 if no such number exists, where A033880 is the abundance of k.

A082732.name: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 3, a(n) = LCM of all the previous terms + 1.
formula: For n>=3, a(n) = A004168(n-3) + 1. - _Max Alekseyev_, Aug 09 2019

1/3 = Sum_{n=3..oo} 1/a(n) = 1/4 + 1/13 + 1/157 + 1/24493 + ... or 1 = Sum_{n=3..oo} 3/a(n) = 3/4 + 3/13 + 3/157 + 3/24493 + .... If we take segment of length 1 and cut off in each step fragment of maximal length such that numerator of fraction is 3, denominators of such fractions will be successive numbers of this sequence. - _Artur Jasinski_, Sep 22 2008

A082733.name: Sum of all entries in character table of the symmetric group S_n.

A082734.name: For n odd, a(n) is the least positive integer not already used. For n even, a(n) is 1 plus the lcm of the last n/2 terms.

formula: a(1) = 1, a(2n) = product of next 2n even numbers. a(2n+1) = product of next 2n+1 odd numbers.

A082736.name: LCM of n-th group of terms in A074147.
formula: a(1) = 1, a(2n) = LCM of next 2n even numbers. a(2n+1) = LCM of next 2n+1 odd numbers.

A082737.name: Triangle read by rows in which the first row contains a 1 and the n-th row contains n primes not included in the previous rows such that the sum of a row is a perfect square.

A082741.name: Numbers that have digits consisting only of line segments or both line segments and curves (base 10 digits are 1, 2, 4, 5, 7).

A082742.name: Indices of occurrences of 2 in A004738.

A082743.name: a(0)=1, a(1)=2; for n >= 2, a(n) is smallest palindrome greater than 1 which is congruent to 1 (mod n).
formula: a(n) = A077528(n) for n >= 2. - _Georg Fischer_, Oct 06 2018

A082744.name: Smallest k such that nk + 1 is a palindrome.

A082746.name: For n odd, a(n) is the least positive integer not already used. For n even, a(n) is the least positive integer not already used that is coprime to a(n/2).

A082747.name: Least k such that k*Mrs(n)*Mrs(n+1)*Mrs(n+2) +1 is prime with Mrs(i)=i-th Mersenne-prime.

A082748.name: Rearrangement of natural numbers disturbing the position of every number such that a(n) is coprime to a(m) if n is coprime to m. ((a(n),a(m)) = 1 if (n,m) = 1.

A082749.name: Difference between the sum of next prime(n) natural numbers and the sum of next n primes.

A082750.name: Triangle read by rows, in which the n-th row contains n smallest numbers not occurring earlier such that the concatenation of terms of a row yields a prime.

A082751.name: Prime formed by concatenation of elements in rows of A082750.

A082754.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n, k) = abs(n^k-k^n), 1<=k<=n.

A082755.name: Smaller of a pair of consecutive primes having only prime digits.

A082756.name: Larger of a pair of consecutive primes having only prime digits.

A082757.name: Possible integer ratios of A/B, where A and B have no 0 in their decimal representation, all decimal digits of A and B are different and each digit is used only once.

A082758.name: Sum of the squares of the trinomial coefficients (A027907).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..2n} T(n, k)^2, where T(n, k) are trinomial coefficients (A027907).
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(2*n-k, k)*binomial(2*n, k). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jul 30 2003
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(2*n,2*k)*binomial(2*k,k) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n+k,2k)*binomial(2*n,n+k). - _Paul Barry_, Dec 16 2008
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k)^2*binomial(2*n,n)/ binomial(2*k,k). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Sep 29 2012
a(n) = sqrt(-3)^(2*n)*P(2*n,-1/sqrt(-3)), where P(n,x) is the Legendre polynomia1  of degree n.

a(n) = (2/Pi)*Integral_{phi=0..Pi/2} ( sin(3*phi))/sin(phi))^(2*n) [Comtet, p. 77, q=3, n=k -> 2*n] = (2/Pi)*Integral_{x=0..2} (x^2 - 1)^(2*n)/sqrt(4-x^2) (with x = 2*cos(phi)). See also the integral of the above comment.

A082759.name: a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..n} binomial(n,k)*trinomial(n,k), where trinomial(n,k) = trinomial coefficients.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..n} C(n+k, n-k)*C(n, k)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 20 2003
a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..n} C(2*n - k, k)*C(n, k)). - _Paul Barry_, Jan 20 2005
G.f.: A(x) = x*B'(x)/B(x), where B(x) satisfies B(x) = x*(1 + 2*B(x) + 2*B(x)^2 + B(x)^3). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Jan 14 2015
a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..n} (-1)^k*C(n, k)*C(3*n - 2*k, n - k). - _Peter Bala_, Jul 13 2016
G.f. y = A(x) satisfies  0 = 1 + y*(3-2*x) + y^3*(-4+20*x+4*x^2+3*x^3). - _Michael Somos_, Oct 15 2016

A082760.name: Trinomial transform of central binomial coefficients (A000984).
formula: a(n) = Sum[ Binomial[2k, k] Trinomial[n, k], {k, 0, 2n} ] where Trinomial[n, k] = trinomial coefficients (A027907)
a(n)=sum{k=0..n, sum{j=0..n, C(n, j)C(j, k)C(2(j+k), j+k)}}; - _Paul Barry_, Feb 15 2005

A082761.name: Trinomial transform of the Fibonacci numbers (A000045).
formula: a(n) = Sum[ Trinomial[n, k] Fibonacci[k+1], {k, 0, 2n} ] where Trinomial[n, k] = trinomial coefficients (A027907).
Third binomial transform of (1, 1, 5, 5, 25, 25, ....). a(n) = ((1+sqrt(5))(3+sqrt(5))^n-(1-sqrt(5))*(3-sqrt(5))^n)/(2*sqrt(5)). - _Paul Barry_, Jul 16 2003
For n>=2: a(n) = 5*a(n-1) + sum_{i=1..n-2} a(i). - _Bob Selcoe_, Mar 18 2014
a(n) = a(-1-n) * 2^(2*n+1) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 18 2014

A082762.name: Trinomial transform of Lucas numbers (A000032).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..2*n} Trinomial(n,k)*Lucas(k+1), where Trinomial(n,k) = trinomial coefficients (A027907).

A082763.name: Roman numeral contains an asymmetric symbol (L).
formula: a(n+50) = a(n) + 100 for n >= 1 [a(n+L) = a(n) + C for n >= I], a(1) = 40 [a(I) = XL], a(n+1) = a(n) + 1 for 1 <= n <= 49 [a(n+I) = a(n) + I for I <= n <= XLIX]; so a(n) = floor((n-1)/50)*100 + 40 + ((n-1)(mod 50)) for n >= 1 [a(n) = floor((n-I)/L)*C + XL + ((n-I)(mod L)) for n >= I].

A082764.name: Trinomial transform of the Pell numbers (A000129).
formula: a(n) = Sum[ Trinomial[n, k] Pell[k], {k, 0, 2n} ] where Trinomial[n, k] = trinomial coefficients (A027907)

A082765.name: Trinomial transform of the factorial numbers (A000142).
formula: a(n) = Sum[ Trinomial[n, k] k!, {k, 0, 2n} ] where Trinomial[n, k] = trinomial coefficients (A027907)

A082766.name: Series ratios converge alternately to sqrt(2) and 1+sqrt(1/2).

A082767.name: Number of edges in the prime graph.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + 1 + omega(n) if n > 1, with a(1) = 1, where omega(n) is the number of distinct prime factors of n.

A082769.name: a(n) = smallest palindromic prime that begins with A082768(n), or 0 if no such number exists.

A082770.name: a(n) = smallest palindromic prime that begins with A082768(n) and contains more than twice the number of digits in A082768(n), or 0 if no such number exists.

A082771.name: Triangular array, read by rows: t(n,k) = Sum(d^k: d|n), 0<=k<n.
formula: t(n, k) = Product(((p^((e(n, p)+1)*k))-1)/(p^k-1): n=Product(p^e(n, p): p prime)), 0<=k<n.

A082772.name: Integers n such that there exists at least one divisor d of n, 1 < d < n, such that d divides n and d+1 divides n+1.

A082773.name: Integers n such that there exists at least one divisor d of n, 1 < d < n, such that d divides n, d+1 divides n+1 and d+2 divides n+2.

A082775.name: Convolution of natural numbers >= 2 and the partition numbers (A000041).
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + A000041(n) + A000070(n) for n>1. - _Alford Arnold_, Dec 10 2007
a(n) = n*A000070(n-2) - A182738(n-2) for n>2. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jun 23 2015

A082776.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest palindromic multiple of a(n-1) obtained by inserting digits anywhere in a(n-1).

A082777.name: a(1) = 2, a(n) = smallest palindromic multiple of a(n-1) obtained by inserting digits anywhere in a(n-1).

a(n) = C(n-1,6) mod 7. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Oct 07 2014

A082785.name: Number of ways n can be written as the sum of a brilliant number and a prime.

A082792.name: Smallest multiple of n beginning with 3.

formula: T(n, j) = T(n-1, j) + T(n-2, j) + T(n-3, j); (every interior number can be obtained by adding the three previous numbers, on its diagonal.)

A082803.name: Smallest multiple of 8 beginning with n.

A082804.name: Smallest multiple of 9 beginning with n.

A082808.name: Palindromic primes whose digit permutation yields at least one other palindromic prime.

A082810.name: Palindromes in which every digit occurs with equal frequency.

A082811.name: Smallest multiple of n beginning with 2.

A082812.name: Positions of sign changes in running sum of mu(k)/k: n such that sign(Sum(k=1..n; mu(k)/k)) <> sign(Sum(k=1..n+1; mu(k)/k)).

A082813.name: Prime numbers of form a^m + b^m + c^m + ..., where a*b*c* ... is the prime factorization of m.

A082816.name: Primitive roots x of sequence A082815.

A082820.name: Product of terms in row n of A082817.

A082821.name: {(Product of terms in row n of A082817) + 1} / n.

A082827.name: Triangle read by rows in which the n-th row contains n numbers not included earlier whose concatenation forms a palindrome.

A082830.name: Decimal expansion of Kempner series Sum_{k>=1, k has no digit 1 in base 10} 1/k.
formula: Equals Sum_{k in A052383\{0}} 1/k, where A052383 = numbers with no digit 1. Those which have a digit 1 (A011531) are omitted in the harmonic sum, and they have asymptotic density 1: almost all terms are omitted from the sum. - _M. F. Hasler_, Jan 15 2020

A082832.name: Decimal expansion of Sum_{k >= 1, k has no digit 3 in base 10} 1/k.
formula: Equals Sum_{k in A052405\{0}} 1/k, where A052405 = numbers with no digit 3. - _M. F. Hasler_, Jan 15 2020

formula: Equals Sum_{k in A052406\{0}} 1/k, where A052406 = numbers with no digit 3. - _M. F. Hasler_, Jan 15 2020

A082834.name: Decimal expansion of Kempner series Sum_{k>=1, k has no digit 5 in base 10} 1/k.

A082837.name: Decimal expansion of Kempner series Sum_{k >= 1, k has no digit 8 in base 10} 1/k.

A082839.name: Decimal expansion of Kempner series Sum_{k >= 1, k has no digit 0 in base 10} 1/k.

A082840.name: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - a(n-2) + 3, with a(0) = -1, a(1) = 1.
formula: E.g.f.: ((1 + sqrt(3))*exp((2 + sqrt(3))*x) + (1 - sqrt(3))*exp((2 - sqrt(3))*x) - 6*exp(x))/4. - _Franck Maminirina Ramaharo_, Nov 12 2018

A082841.name: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - a(n-2) for n>1, a(0)=3, a(1)=9.
formula: a(n) = sqrt(3/2)*(a^(n+1/2) + b^(n+1/2)), with a=2+sqrt(3) and b=2-sqrt(3).

A082842.name: Numbers a(n) have a representation a(n) = x^2 + y^2 and x is least primitive root of a(n). a(n) is first such number with x increasing in the sequence, x can be found in A082843.

A082843.name: Primitive roots x of sequence A082842.

A082844.name: Start with 3,2 and apply the rule a(a(1)+a(2)+...+a(n)) = a(n), fill in any undefined terms with a(t) = 2 if a(t-1) = 3 and a(t) = 3 if a(t-1) = 2.

A082846.name: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2, a(3) = 3; then a(a(1)+a(2)+..+a(k)) = a(k) and fill the "holes" using the rule : a(m) = 1 if a(m-1) = 3, a(m) = 2 if a(m-1) = 1, a(m) = 3 if a(m-1) = 2.
formula: It seems that limit n ->infinity (1/n)*sum(k=1, n, a(k))= C >2 (C=2.07...)

A082847.name: Partial sums of A082846.
formula: It seems that limit n-->infinity of a(n)/n = C > 2 (C=2.07...)

A082849.name: Product of cototient values of consecutive integers.
formula: Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ c * n^3 + O(n^2 * log(n)^2), where c = (1/3) * (1 + Product_{p prime} (1 - 2/p^2)) - 4/Pi^2 = 0.03559329841.... (Panaitopol, 1999). - _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 09 2021

A082850.name: Let S(0) = {}, S(n) = {S(n-1), S(n-1), n}; sequence gives S(infinity).
formula: a(2^m-1) = m. If n = 2^m-1 + k, with 0 < k < 2^m, then a(n) = a(k). - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Aug 16 2006

A082853.name: Integers 0 to Catalan(n)-1 followed by integers 0 to Catalan(n+1)-1 etc.

A082854.name: Integers 1 to Catalan(n) followed by integers 1 to Catalan(n+1) etc.

A082857.name: Inverse function of N -> N injection A082856.

A082860.name: Array A(x,y): the least common supertree (union) of the binary trees x and y, (x,y) running as (0,0),(1,0),(0,1),(2,0),(1,1),(0,2) and each index referring to a binary tree encoded by A014486(j).

A082862.name: Prime(2^j) at which (prime(1+2^n)-prime(2^n))/log(prime(2^n)) sets a (low) record.

A082863.name: Number of distinct prime factors of n^2-1.

A082864.name: Decimal expansion of (-1)*c(2) where, in a neighborhood of zero, Gamma(x) = 1/x + c(0) + c(1)*x + c(2)*x^2 + ... (Gamma(x) denotes the Gamma function).
formula: c(2) = (EulerGamma^3 - 3*EulerGamma*zeta(2) + zeta(3))/6 = -0.24234545222... ( where EulerGamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant (A001620)).

A082865.name: a(n) is the sum of the preceding terms that are coprime to n.

A082866.name: a(1)=1, a(2)=2, otherwise a(n) is the sum of the preceding terms a(j), 1<=j<n, where gcd(n,j)=1.

A082867.name: Numbers n such that there exists a divisor m where m divides n and m+1 divides n+1, but there is no divisor d such that d divides n, d+1 divides n+1 and d+2 divides n+2.

A082868.name: Continued fraction approximation to Product(k=2..inf; Zeta(k)).

A082870.name: Tribonacci array.
formula: G.f.: x/(1 - x - x^2*y - x^3*y^2). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, May 30 2003

A082871.name: First component x of pairs (x,y) where x <= y and x!+y! is a square, sorted on x.

A082872.name: a^n + b^n + c^n + ..., where a*b*c* ... is the prime factorization of n.

A082873.name: Independence number of king KG_2 on triangle board B_n.

A082874.name: Independence number of king KG_4 on triangle board B_n.

A082875.name: Squares that are the sum of three factorials.

A082876.name: Number of prime divisors (counted with multiplicity) of numbers of form a^n + b^n + c^n + ..., where a*b*c* ... is the prime factorization of n.

A082878.name: Arithmetic derivative of numbers of the form p*q^k with distinct primes p and q, k>0.

A082879.name: Number of primes not exceeding factorial of n-th prime.

A082880.name: Largest value of A075860(j) when j runs through composite numbers between n-th and (n+1)-th primes. That is, the largest fixed-point[=prime] reached by iteration of A008472(=sum of prime factors) initiated with composite values between two consecutive primes.

A082881.name: Least value of A075860(j) when j runs through composite numbers between n-th and (n+1)-th primes. That is, the smallest fixed-point[=prime] reached by iteration of function A008472(=sum of prime factors) initiated with composite values between two consecutive primes.

A082882.name: Number of distinct values of A075860(j) when j runs through composite numbers between n-th and (n+1)-th primes. That is, the counts of different fixed-points[=prime] reached by iteration of function A008472(=sum of prime factors) initiated with composite values between two consecutive primes.

A082883.name: Primes p(x) satisfying the following conditions: [1]# A082882(x)=1; [2]# {p(x),p(x+1)} are not twin primes; [3]# values of A075860(j) for j composites between these two non-twin primes are identical. See also A075860, A082880-A082882.

A082884.name: a(n) = smallest prime p for which (r-p)/log(p) < 1/n, where r is the next prime after p.
formula: a(n)=min{prime(j): A001223(j)/log(prime(j)) < 1/n}, where prime(j)=A000040(j) is the j-th prime.

A082885.name: Primes followed by a larger-than-average prime gap.

A082886.name: floor((prime(n+1)-prime(n))/log(prime(n))).
formula: Infinitely often a(n) >> log log n log log log log n/log log log n, see Ford-Green-Konyagin-Maynard-Tao. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Sep 04 2015

A082888.name: Primes p such that (r-p)/log(p) > 3, where r is the next prime after p.

A082889.name: Primes p such that (r-p)/log(p) > 4, where r is the next prime after p.

A082890.name: Primes p such that (r-p)/log(p) > 5, where r is the next prime after p.

A082891.name: Smallest prime p[j] such that quotient q[j], obtained when consecutive prime differences are divided by logarithm of smaller prime,p[j], is larger than n.

A082892.name: Floor(q(j)), where q(j) = 2j/log(A000230(j)); log is natural logarithm, 2j-s are prime gaps > 1, A000230(j) is the minimal lesser prime opening the consecutive prime distance equals 2j.

A082893.name: a(n) is the closest number to n-th prime which is divisible by n.
formula: a(n)=n*floor[(floor(n/2)+p(n))/n], where p(n) is the n-th prime.

A082894.name: a(n) is the closest number to 2^n which is divisible by n.

A082895.name: Closest number to sigma(n) = A000203(n) which is divisible by n.

A082896.name: a(n) = A082893(n)/n.
formula: a(n) = floor((floor(n/2) + p(n))/n), where p(n) is the n-th prime.

A082897.name: Perfect totient numbers.
formula: n is a perfect totient number if S(n) = n, where S(n) = phi(n) + phi^2(n) +  ... + 1, where phi is Euler's totient function and phi^2(n) = phi(phi(n)), ..., phi^k(n) = phi(phi^(k-1)(n)).
n such that 2n = A053478(n). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jul 02 2004
n log log log log n << a(n) <= 3^n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Mar 22 2012

A082898.name: a(n) = A082895(n)/n, where A082895(n) is the closest number to sigma(n) which is divisible by n.

A082899.name: a(n) = A082893(n)-A000040(n), that is difference of n-th prime and number closest to it and divisible by n.
formula: a(n)=p[n]-n*floor[(floor(n/2)+p[n])/n], where p[n] is the n-th prime.

A082900.name: a(n) = A082894(n)-A000079(n), that is difference of 2^n and the number closest to it and divisible by n.

A082901.name: a(n) = A082895(n)-A000203(n); the distance from sigma(n) to that multiple of n which is closest to sigma(n), positive terms for cases where the closest multiple is after sigma(n), and negative terms where it is before sigma(n). In case of ties, a positive term is selected.

A082904.name: Triangle read by rows: Pascal's triangle restricted to binomial(n, d) where d is a divisor of n.

A082905.name: Modified Pascal-triangle, read by rows. All C(n,j) binomial coefficients are replaced by C(n/g, j/g), where g = gcd(n,j).

A082906.name: Sum of terms in n-th row of modified Pascal's triangle displayed in A082905.

A082907.name: A modified Pascal's triangle, read by rows, and modified as follows: binomial(n,j) is replaced by gcd(2^n, binomial(n,j)), i.e., the largest power of 2 dividing binomial(n,j).

A082908.name: Largest value of gcd(2^n, binomial(n,j)) with j=0..n-1; maximal value of largest power of 2 dividing binomial(n,j) in the n-th row of Pascal's triangle.

A082912.name: Least k such that H(k) > 10^n, where H(k) is the harmonic number Sum_{i=1..k} 1/i.

A082913.name: Least k such that H(k) > 2^n, where H(k) is the harmonic number Sum_{i=1..k} 1/i.

A082915.name: Numbers n for which the first difference sequence of A054040 decreases.

A082916.name: Numbers k such that k and binomial(2*k, k) are relatively prime.
formula: It seems that a(n) is asymptotic to c*n*log(n) with 0.7<c<0.8.

A082917.name: Numbers n with property that n can be written in more ways as a sum of two odd primes than any smaller even number.

A082918.name: Record setting entries in A002375 (number of decompositions into two odd primes).

A082919.name: Numbers n such that n, n+2, n+4, n+6, n+8, n+10, n+12 and n+14 are semiprimes.

A082920.name: Squares that are the sum of four factorials.

A082921.name: Sort the digits of these squares into descending order and drop zeros to get primes.

A082922.name: Numbers n such that when the digits of Fibonacci(n) are sorted into decreasing order and zeros are dropped it is a prime.

A082923.name: Sort the digits of these triangular numbers into descending order and drop zeros to get primes.

A082924.name: For n prime, a(n) = n+1; for n even and > 2, a(n) = n/2; otherwise a(n) = 3*n.

A082926.name: Difference between the number of primes equal to or less than n and the number of nonsquarefree numbers equal to or less than n.
formula: a(n) = |Q(n) - P(n)| where Q(n) = number of nonsquarefree numbers less than or equal to n and P(n) = number of primes less than or equal to n.

A082927.name: Numbers such that at least one pair of adjacent digits are consecutive.
formula: a(n) = n + O(x^0.915), where the exponent is the log(k)/log(10) with k the largest root of x^5 - 9x^4 + 4x^3 + 21x^2 - 9x - 5. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Mar 11 2014

A082928.name: If n is prime, a(n) = n+1; if n is even, a(n) = n/2; otherwise a(n) = n.
formula: a(n) = A026741(n) + A010051(n), for n>2; with a(1) = 1, a(2) = 3. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Oct 04 2014

A082931.name: a(1) = 1; a(n) = least k > a(n-1) such that a(i)+k is prime for some i < n and each prime of form a(i)+a(j) occurs for unique i <= j.

A082934.name: A082928(1) + A082928(2) + ... + A082928(n).
formula: seq = if n even then n/2 else n. seq = if n is prime then n+1. Sumseq = Sumseq + seq for n=1, 2, ...

A082935.name: Smallest palindrome beginning with n and a digit sum of n at some stage.

A082936.name: a(n) = (1/(3*n))*Sum_{d|n, d even} phi(2*n/d)*binomial(3d/2,d).
formula: a(n) = sum( d divides n, phi(n/d) * C(3*d,d) ) / (3*n) for n>=1, a(0)=1.
a(n) = sum( d divides n, phi(n/d) * C(3*d-1,d) ) / (2*n) for n>=1, a(0)=1.

A082937.name: Palindromes divisible by all its digits.

A082939.name: Numbers such that sum of the digits of the product of the factorial of digits of the number is equal to the sum of the digits of the number.

A082941.name: Palindromes starting with n such that the sum of the digits of the product of the factorial of n and reverse of n is equal to the center digit.

A082943.name: Numbers not divisible by any of their digits nor by the sum of their digits.

A082944.name: Palindromes starting from n such that sum of the digits of n and reverse of n is the center digit.

A082945.name: Numbers n which in decimal have the form imj, where m is the middle digit, with property that j is the reversal of i, and i = m*j.

A082947.name: Palindromes not divisible by any of their digits.

A082948.name: Palindromes neither divisible by any of their digits nor by the sum of their digits.

A082949.name: Numbers of the form p^q * q^p, with distinct primes p and q.

A082950.name: Power base and exponent of n-th prime-power exchanged.

A082951.name: Number of primitive (aperiodic) word structures of length n using an infinite alphabet.
formula: a(n) = sum mu(c)*A000110(d) over all cd=n; equivalently, A000110(n) = sum a(k), where the sum is over all k|n.
1 + Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/(1 - x^n) is the g.f. of A000110. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Mar 05 2018

A082952.name: Smaller of the two factors of the n-th semiprime number of the form m!+1.
formula: Numbers p such that p*q=A078778(n)!+1, p, q prime, p<q

A082953.name: a(n) = A000252(n) / A070732(n).
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e) = 2^(2e-1) and a(p^e) = (p-1)^2*p^(2e-2) for p > 2. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 14 2011
a(n) = phi(n)^2 if n odd; 2*phi(n)^2 if n even, where phi(n) = A000010(n). - _Jianing Song_, Apr 20 2019

A082956.name: Difference between C(n) and the first prime after C(n), where C(n) is A049614, product of composite numbers less than or equal to n.

A082957.name: Numbers n such that sigma(2n) < sigma(2n+1).
formula: Conjecture : a(n) is asymptotic to c*n where 18<c<18.5.

A082958.name: Number of symmetric short bushes with n edges.
formula: a(n) has antiparity of A007814(n+1), i.e. a(n) mod 2 = A035263(n+1). - _Ralf Stephan_, Feb 21 2004

A082959.name: Number of inequivalent optimal linear codes of length 2n over GF(4).

A082960.name: Number of inequivalent optimal Hermitian self-dual codes of length 2n over GF(4).

A082961.name: Number of inequivalent optimal Hermitian formally self-dual but not self-dual codes of length 2n over GF(4).

A082962.name: Numerators of continued fraction convergents to (sqrt(37)-4)/3.

A082963.name: Number of n X n 0-1 matrices with half 1's and half 0's (rounded up/down if odd).

A082964.name: a(n) = m given by arctan(tan(n)) = n - m*Pi.

A082966.name: Number of inequivalent ways (mod D_4) three checkers can be placed on an n X n board.

A082967.name: Numbers n such that mu(n) + mu(n+1) + mu(n+2) + mu(n+3) + mu(n+4) + mu(n+5) + mu(n+6) = 6.

A082968.name: a(n)=sum(k=1,n, k modulo(sum(i=0,k-1,1-t(i))) where t(i)=A010060(i) is the Thue-Morse sequence.
formula: Despite the definition, a(n) has an unexpectedly simple asymptotic behavior h: a(n)=(n/4)^2 +O(n) and more precisely it appears that : (n/4)^2-n/8 <= a(n) < (n/4)^2+n/2 with equality (on left side) for infinitely many values of n.

A082969.name: Numbers n such that (n/4)^2-n/8=sum(k=1,n, k modulo(sum(i=0,k-1,1-t(i))) where t(i)=A010060(i) is the Thue-Morse sequence.
formula: It appears that for n>=1 a(n+2)=8*A000069(n)+2 (where A000069(n) are the odious numbers).

A082970.name: Number of permutations of length n containing 2 occurrences of 132.

A082971.name: Number of permutations of {1,2,...,n} containing exactly 3 occurrences of the 132 pattern.

A082973.name: Fibonacci numbers which are of the form Sum{i=1..k} prime(i) for some k.

A082975.name: Denominators of continued fraction convergents to (sqrt(37)-4)/3.
formula: a(n+3) = 12*a(n) + a(n-3),  a(n+1) = a(n-1) + (1+mod(n, 3))*a(n) for all n in Z.

A082977.name: Numbers that are congruent to {0, 1, 3, 5, 6, 8, 10} mod 12.
formula: a(n) = a(n-7) + 12 for n > 7. - _Jianing Song_, Sep 22 2018

A082979.name: Lexicographically earliest rearrangement of primes such that the sum of two consecutive terms is a palindrome.

A082980.name: Rearrangement of triangular numbers such that the sum of two consecutive terms is a palindrome.

A082981.name: Start with the sequence S(0)={1,1} and for k>0 define S(k) to be I(S(k-1)) where I denotes the operation of inserting, for i=1,2,3..., the term a(i)+a(i+1) between any two terms for which 4a(i+1)<=5a(i). The listed terms are the initial terms of the limit of this process as k goes to infinity.

A082982.name: Numbers n such that n, n+1 and n+2 are sums of 2 squares.

A082983.name: Odd numbers which lead to 1 in the 3x+1 problem, generated by a particular "least-first" greedy algorithm (see program code).

A082984.name: Numbers n for which the 3x+1 problem takes at least n halving and tripling steps to reach 1.

A082985.name: Coefficient table for Chebyshev's U(2*n,x) polynomial expanded in decreasing powers of (-4*(1-x^2)).
formula: Triangle read by rows: row #n has n+1 terms. T(n,0)=1, T(n,n)=2n+1, T(n,m) = T(n-1,m-1) + Sum_{k=0..m} T(n-1-k, m-k).
T(k, s) = ((2k+1)/(2s+1))*binomial(k+s, 2s), 0 <= s <= k; then transpose the triangle. - _Gary W. Adamson_, May 29 2003

Signed version: a(n,m)=0 if n < m, otherwise a(n,m) = ((-1)^m)*binomial(2*n+1-m,m)*(2*n+1)/(2*n+1-m). From the Rivlin reference, p. 37, eq.(1.92), using the differential eq. for T(2*n+1,x). Also from Waring's formula.

Signed version: a(n,m)=0 if n < m, otherwise a(n,m) = ((-1)^m)*(Sum_{k=0..n-m} binomial(m+k,k)*binomial(2*n+1,2*(k+m))/2^(2*(n-m)). Proof: De Moivre's formula for cos((2*n+1)*phi) rewritten in terms of odd powers of cos(phi). Cf. Rivlin reference p. 4, eq.(1.10).
Signed version: a(n,m) = A084930(n,n-m)/2^(2*(n-m)) (scaled coefficients of Chebyshev's T(2*n+1,x)), decreasing odd powers).
Unsigned version: a(n,m)=0 if n < m, otherwise a(n,m) = binomial(2*n-m,m)*(2*n+1)/(2*(n-m)+1). From the differential eq. for U(2*n,x). (End)
Sum_{i>=0} T(n-i, n-2*i)*4^i = 3^n = A000244(n). - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 24 2012
T(r,k) = binomial(2*r-k,k-1) + binomial(2*r-1-k,k-2) with 1 <= r and 1 <= k <= r.
For a given n, one gets r = floor((1+sqrt(8*n))/2), k = n-(r^2-r)/2, a(n) = binomial(2*r-k,k-1) + binomial(2*r-1-k,k-2). (End)

A082986.name: Largest x such that 1/x + 1/y + 1/z = 1/n.
formula: a(n) >= n^4 + 2n^3 + 2n^2 + n (cf. A169938). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Oct 17 2012. [Note this is at present only a lower bound! - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jan 27 2014]
a(n) >= 6*A006325(n-1). -  _Robert G. Wilson v_, May 04 2013 [Corrected by _Michael Somos_, Jan 27 2014]
a(n) < 3*n^4 for n>=2 (upper bound). - _Carmine Suriano_, Feb 20 2014

A082987.name: a(n)=sum(k=0,n,3^k*F(k)) where F(k) is the k-th Fibonacci number.

A082988.name: a(n)=sum(k=0,n,4^k*F(k)) where F(k) is the k-th Fibonacci number.

A082989.name: Number of ordered trees with n edges and having no root-to-leaf branches.

A082990.name: Rent due for landing on undeveloped Monopoly properties starting at Mediterranean Avenue and finishing at Boardwalk, not including railroads or utilities.

A082991.name: a(1) = 1 and for n > 1, a(n) = 2 * length of the cycle reached for the map x -> A062401(x), starting at n [where A062401(n) = phi(sigma(n))], or -1 if no finite cycle is ever reached.
formula: a(1) = 1; for n > 1, a(n) = 2*A095955(n). [See comments.] - _Antti Karttunen_, Nov 07 2017

A082992.name: Primes whose 10's complement is a triangular number.

A082994.name: Numbers n such that all the following properties hold: (i) n*reverse(n) is a square; (ii) n != reverse(n); (iii) n and reverse(n) are not both squares; and (iv) n and reverse(n) have the same number of digits.

A082995.name: Distance from n!+1 to next larger square.

A083000.name: Values of x for which 9y^2 = x^2 + 2xy - 2x has integer solutions with positive y.
